<Author>Boingercat
<Content>Overall, a Very Good Experience We stayed for 5 nights at The Inn at St. Botolph. Overall, it was a great experience. We booked a 1-bedroom suite (kitchenette, living room, bedroom, bathroom), and it was an adequate size for ourselves and our 6-year old son. There was plenty of closet storage as well. The many windows made it bright during the day, but the room-darkening curtains made it sufficiently dark for sleeping.The staff were consistently polite and helpful, and were immediately responsive to any of our needs. They even called us back when we tried to call them but got no answer--even though we didn't leave a message! Our room was very quiet, and we couldn't hear the elevator, which was right next to our room. The location couldn't be better (5-10 minutes to everything), and overnight parking was only 1-1/2 blocks away, at the Prudential Center parking garage. There are a few things to take into consideration if you're planning to stay as a family with younger children at the Inn at St. Botolph. First, the kitchenette is not completely family-friendly. For example, it was stocked with 12 or so champagne and wine glasses, but there was not a cereal bowl to be found. The plastic drinking glasses were so huge that they were unmanageable for smaller hands, and there was no trash can for kitchen trash. But the nearly full-size refrigerator/ freezer (with auto ice maker) was a tremendous asset, as were the toaster oven and two-burner stove top. The black rubber floor in the kitchenette and bathroom was probably not a great choice for a hotel room--they looked dirty, even when cleaned.As for sleeping arrangements, the Inn provided an Aerobed for our son at our request, but the bedroom was too small to accommodate it (also, the queen bed canopy-type frame was also way too big for such a small room, and made it difficult to move around in the room--a lower headboard/footboard configuration would have been more appropriate). Putting the Aerobed in the living room was impractical, given our varied sleep schedules.Finally, to be fully family-friendly, a bathtub instead of just a shower stall would have been helpful. The bathroom was clean and nicely arranged, and there was plenty of room on both sides of the sink to put our belongings. The towels and comfy bathrobe were of obviously high quality.We will definitely stay at the Inn at St. Botolph's again, and would recommend the hotel to others. But be aware that their cancellation policy dictates no refund if you cancel less than two weeks in advance, and it will cost you $50 if you cancel earlier than that. 
<Date>Dec 10, 2008
